ans to attend the University of California, Berkeley, at that time. Giving a personal perspective on the conflicts of living in and between cultures, this eloquent story provides a rare glimpse into the life of a young Mexican American woman who achieved her dreams of obtaining a university education.In addition to the many fascinating details of everyday life the narrative provides, Mario T. García's introduction contextualizes the place and importance of Tywoniak's life. Both introduction and narrative illustrate the process by which Tywoniak negotiated her relation to ethnic identity and cultural allegiances, the ways in which she came to find education as a channel for breaking with fieldwork patterns of life, and the effect of migration on family and culture. This deeply personal memoir portrays a courageous Mexican American woman moving between many cultural worlds, a life story that at times parallels, and at times diverges from, the real life experiences of thousands of other, unnamed women.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMexican American college studentszCaliforniazBerkeleyvBiography. 0aMexican American migrant agricultural laborersvBiography. 0aMexican American womenxEthnic identity. 0aMexican American womenzCaliforniavBiography. 0aMexican American womenzCaliforniaxEthnic identityvBiography. 0aMexican American womenzNew MexicovBiography. 0aMexican American women. 4aGender Studies. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aEsquibel Tywoniak, Frances, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGarcía, Mario T. , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGarcía, Mario T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity o